+slide_middle
  .handout \textbf{Question}
    .notes How do humans come to know  about---and to knowingly manipulate---objects, causes, words, numbers, colours, actions and minds?
  p.center the question
  .notes Have we made any progress?


+slide_middle
  p.center case-by-case
  .notes If you're wondering what the big idea is, there isn't one.
  .notes I think progress depends on approaching it case by case.
  .notes For instance, we considered the role of language in two cases, knowledge of colour and knowledge of minds.
  .notes It seems to play quite different roles in these two cases.
  .notes So while it seems plausible that abilities to communicate by language do play a role in explaining the emergence of knowledge in many domains, it's hard to assign it one role.
  .notes There are themes running across the cases but little in the way of general principles.
  .notes I'm not saying that's a bad thing; that's just how it is.
  
+slide_middle
  p.center core knowledge
  .notes Core knowledge is initially a label for a problem.
  .notes With respect to various domains of knowledge including colour, physics and psychology, infants have some but not all of the capacities that are characteristic of knowledge.
  .notes So we face a dilemma.
  .notes The simplest explanation of what they can do would be to ascribe them knowledge.
  .notes But ascribing them knowledge systematically generates false predictions about what they will do.
  .notes So it must be wrong to ascribe them knowledge.
  .notes In the first instance, ‘core knowledge’ (or modular cognition, or implicit knowledge, or tacit knowledge) is just a label for whatever it is that is not knowledge but explains these capacities.
  
+slide_middle
  p.center adults, automaticity and limits
  .notes Developmental evidence for core knowledge is fragile:
  .notes it is always possble that the apparently incorrect predictions can be explained just by appeal to performance factors.
  .notes Now as I understand the science many attempts to do this have failed.
  .notes But for all we know this may be due only to the limited ingenuity of the researchers.
  .notes Reflection on adults provides us with a second line of converging evidence.
  
  .notes To say that a process is automatic is ...
  .notes We're looking for two features in adults:
  .notes (i) apparent conflict in what the adults know depending on whether the response is automatic or controlled,
  .notes and (ii) limits of adults' automatic competence match those of infants'.
  .notes We found some evidence this pattern in (a) colour; (b) mindreading; (c) number; (d) maybe causation and physical objects (representational momentum \citep{kozhevnikov:2001_impetus}).

