+slide_middle
  p.center Core knowlegde: is it all one thing?
  .notes Patterns in the mindreading case seem different from patterns in the cases of physics and number.
  .notes Most people are committed to there being different stories for (a) colour (categorical perception); (b) syntax (tacit knowledge); and (c) physical objects.
  .notes I'm not sure.  I'm tempted to think that perceptual and motor cognition are at the root of these in every case, but this is a radical idea for which there is currenly very little evidence.

+slide_middle
  p.center What is innate in humans?
  .notes Conclusive evidence is rare, but that's not really an obstacle.
  .notes There's no reason to take radical anti-nativism as our starting point.
  .notes This question has two aspects: (i) what sort of thing; (ii) what particulars in which domains.
  .notes On (i), I like the idea that core knowledge is innate.
  .notes But we should be more careful and say at most that either core knowledge or something capable of priming the acquisition of core knowledge is innate.
  .notes On (ii), we looked at a paradigm case, knowledge of syntax.
  .notes In this case, we used a poverty of stimulus argument.
  .notes While the evidence is less clear in other cases, there is certainly reason to suppose that poverty of stimulus arguments might work for knowledge of colour and knowledge of physical objects.
  .notes But I also tried to argue that deciding this question probably isn't very important from our point of view.


+slide_middle
  p.center social interaction
  .notes We've seen that cooperative forms of social interaction appear early in development.
  .notes We studied pointing but there are examples involving helping and playing together too.
  .notes In seminars we've been considering two ideas:
  .notes (i) there is a form of cooperative social interaction abilities to engage in which are important for explaining the origins of knowledge of others' perspectives, for explaining the emergence of abilities to communicate by language, and norms.
  .notes (ii) these forms of cooperative social interaction involve a capacity for shared intentionality,
  .notes where shared intentionality is understood as the ability to share mental states.

+slide({bkg:'slide_romantic_notions_of_sharing.jpg'})
